      "id": "based-every-junior-dev-ill",
      "source": "Community sourced"
    },
    {
      "text": "The best investment you can make is in yourself. The second best is in tools that save you time. The worst is in courses that save you nothing.",
      "author": "based",
      "author_slug": "based",
      "categories": [
        "productivity"
      ],
      "tags": [
        "investment",
        "learning"
      ],
      "grug_level": 3,
      "spiciness": 3,
      "id": "based-the-best-investment-you",
      "source": "Community sourced"
    },
    {
      "text": "Fail fast, fail forward, fail cheaply. But most importantly: learn.",
      "author": "based",
      "author_slug": "based",
      "categories": [
        "business",
        "entrepreneur"
      ],
      "tags": [
        "failure",
        "learning"
      ],
      "grug_level": 3,
      "spiciness": 2,
      "id": "based-fail-fast-fail-forward",
      "source": "Community sourced"
    },
    {
      "text": "Side projects are the best way to learn. Main projects are the best way to earn. You need both.",
      "author": "based",
      "author_slug": "based",
      "categories": [
        "indie-hacker"
      ],
      "tags": [
        "learning",
        "earning"
      ],
      "grug_level": 3,
      "spiciness": 2,
      "id": "based-side-projects-are-the",
      "source": "Community sourced"
    },
    {
      "text": "Your first product taught you everything. Your second product teaches you what actually matters.",
      "author": "based",
      "author_slug": "based",
      "categories": [
        "indie-hacker"
      ],
      "tags": [
        "learning",
        "iteration"
      ],
      "grug_level": 3,
      "spiciness": 2,
      "id": "based-your-first-product-taught",
      "source": "Community sourced"
    },
    {
      "text": "The best time to learn about security is before you get hacked. The second best time is after. The worst time is never.",
      "author": "based",
      "author_slug": "based",
      "categories": [
        "engineering"
      ],
      "tags": [
        "security",
        "learning"
      ],
      "grug_level": 3,
      "spiciness": 2,
      "id": "based-the-best-time-to",
      "source": "Community sourced"
    },
    {
      "text": "The best time to learn a new language is when you need it. The worst is when you think it'll make you a better programmer.",
      "author": "based",
      "author_slug": "based",
      "categories": [
        "engineering"
      ],
      "tags": [
        "languages",
        "learning"
      ],
      "grug_level": 3,
      "spiciness": 2,
      "id": "based-the-best-time-to",
      "source": "Community sourced"
    },
    {
      "text": "The best business model is one where you get paid to learn.",
      "author": "based",
      "author_slug": "based",
      "categories": [
        "business"
      ],
      "tags": [
        "business-model",
        "learning"
      ],
      "grug_level": 3,
      "spiciness": 2,
      "id": "based-the-best-business-model",
      "source": "Community sourced"
    },
    {
      "text": "Every production incident is a lesson. If you're not learning from them, you're just collecting them.",
      "author": "based",
      "author_slug": "based",
      "categories": [
        "engineering",
        "devops"
      ],
      "tags": [
        "incidents",
        "learning"
      ],
      "grug_level": 3,
      "spiciness": 2,
      "id": "based-every-production-incident-is",
      "source": "Community sourced"
    },
    {
      "text": "The best way to learn is to teach. The best way to teach is to build something that explains itself.",
      "author": "based",
      "author_slug": "based",
      "categories": [
        "productivity",
        "engineering"
      ],
      "tags": [
        "learning",
        "teaching"
      ],
      "grug_level": 3,
      "spiciness": 2,
      "id": "based-the-best-way-to",
      "source": "Community sourced"
    },
    {
      "text": "The best way to get better at coding is to code. Not to watch tutorials. Not to read books. To code.",
      "author": "based",
      "author_slug": "based",
      "categories": [
        "productivity",
        "engineering"
      ],
      "tags": [
        "learning",
        "practice"
      ],
      "grug_level": 3,
      "spiciness": 2,
      "id": "based-the-best-way-to",
      "source": "Community sourced"
    },
    {
      "text": "Your first product failure isn't a failure. It's tuition. You just paid for a masterclass.",
      "author": "based",
      "author_slug": "based",
      "categories": [
        "indie-hacker"
      ],
      "tags": [
        "failure",
        "learning"
      ],
      "grug_level": 3,
      "spiciness": 2,
      "id": "based-your-first-product-failure",
      "source": "Community sourced"
    },
    {
      "text": "Your side project is your playground. Play. Experiment. Break things. That's how you learn.",
      "author": "based",
      "author_slug": "based",
      "categories": [
        "indie-hacker"
      ],
      "tags": [
        "side-projects",
        "learning"
      ],
      "grug_level": 3,
      "spiciness": 2,
      "id": "based-your-side-project-is",
      "source": "Community sourced"
    },
    {
      "text": "Every mistake is a lesson. Every lesson makes you better. Fail fast, learn faster.",
      "author": "based",
      "author_slug": "based",
      "categories": [
        "wisdom"
      ],
      "tags": [
        "failure",
        "learning"
      ],
      "grug_level": 3,
      "spiciness": 2,
      "id": "based-every-mistake-is-a",
      "source": "Community sourced"
    },
    {
      "text": "The best way to learn is to fail. The second best is to learn from someone else's failure.",
      "author": "based",
      "author_slug": "based",
      "categories": [
        "wisdom"
      ],
      "tags": [
        "failure",
        "learning"
      ],
      "grug_level": 3,
